And the roof. The roof. Forty thousand. ~I sit under it every Sunday.~ The roof is — the roof is the indulgence letter. Thesis twenty-seven. *The money clinks in the chest.* That is what the money was for, friend. Not the rain. The rain was the cover story. The money was for — the money was for what the pastor said this morning. *Pillar. Generosity. We know where he is now.* That sermon cost forty thousand dollars. I was sitting in the pew it bought.

*A long pause. He looks down at the dust on his knees as if surprised to find himself there.*

And I — I read this passage to children, friend. I read it to *children.* I told them — *the least of these means everyone, it means you have to see everyone* — and I went home and I ate dinner under that roof. I knew what it was. ~I knew, and I sat anyway.~ I knew in October. I knew in November. I knew the morning of the budget meeting. I knew when I shook his hand at the Christmas service. I knew this morning when the pastor stood up and I —

