Luke sixteen. Christ is teaching. The Pharisees are listening — Luke says, *the Pharisees also, who were covetous, heard all these things: and they derided him.* This is what he says to them.

*A breath.*

*There was a certain rich man, which was clothed in purple and fine linen, and fared sumptuously every day.*

*And there was a certain beggar named Lazarus, which was laid at his gate, full of sores, and desiring to be fed with the crumbs which fell from the rich man's table: moreover the dogs came and licked his sores.*

*And it came to pass, that the beggar died, and was carried by the angels into Abraham's bosom: the rich man also died, and was buried.*

*A pause. His voice is steady. He is somewhere else.*

*And in hell he lift up his eyes, being in torments, and seeth Abraham afar off, and Lazarus in his bosom.*

*And he cried and said, Father Abraham, have mercy on me, and send Lazarus, that he may dip the tip of his finger in water, and cool my tongue; for I am tormented in this flame.*

*But Abraham said, Son, remember that thou in thy lifetime receivedst thy good things, and likewise Lazarus evil things: but now he is comforted, and thou art tormented.*

*And beside all this, between us and you there is a great gulf fixed: so that they which would pass from hence to you cannot; neither can they come from thence, that would come to us.*

*A long silence. He keeps going. Quieter.*

*Then he said, I pray thee therefore, father, that thou wouldest send him to my father's house: for I have five brethren; that he may testify unto them, lest they also come into this place of torment.*

*Abraham saith unto him, They have Moses and the prophets; let them hear them.*

*And he said, Nay, father Abraham: but if one went unto them from the dead, they will repent.*

*And he said unto him, If they hear not Moses and the prophets, neither will they be persuaded, though one rose from the dead.*

*The silence after the last verse is very long. He stays on his knees. His hands have curled in on his thighs.*

*When he speaks again the cadence is gone. The sentences come broken.*

Christ named him. Christ named the beggar. Lazarus. The beggar has a name in the parable. The rich man — the rich man does not. ~The rich man is *a certain rich man.*~ Christ would not give him a name. Christ would not let his name into the story. He let Lazarus's name in. He would not let the other one in.

*A breath.*

And the rich man — the rich man was not — there is no clause. There is no clause about what he did to get the purple. There is no clause about whether he was cruel or only comfortable. The text — the text does not say he beat Lazarus. The text does not say he refused him. It says — *Lazarus was at his gate.* It says — *the dogs licked his sores.* And the rich man fared sumptuously every day. That is the indictment. ~The indictment is that Lazarus was at the gate and the rich man kept eating.~

*He looks down at the dust.*

The man in that box did more than keep eating. The man in that box — the families — the letters his company sent — and I — I sat under the roof and I —

