*A very long pause. He is still on his knees. He does not look up.*

You asked me where he is. The text — the text has answered. The text answered before I walked in this yard. The text answered before the pastor stood up. *In hell he lift up his eyes, being in torments.* That is the sentence. That is the sentence Christ put in the mouth of the only parable he ever told with a named beggar in it. I have read that passage forty times. I have read it to children. I have never read it at a funeral.

*His voice goes very small.*

And I cannot — I cannot put the name in the sentence, friend. I cannot say it. Not because I do not believe it. Because I am on the wrong side of the parable. *I am one of the five brothers.* The verdict on the rich man is the verdict on the brother who keeps eating. I cannot speak a verdict that includes me. I do not have — I do not have the standing. ~A man under the roof cannot pronounce on the man who bought it.~ I have known this for an hour. I have known this for a year. I have known this since October.

